\layout Subsection

Self-Similarity on the Poincare Disk
\layout Standard

There is one interesting mapping whose properties are worth reviewing, and
 that is the mapping of the upper half-plane to the Poincare disk.
 This mapping is curious because it is not infrequent in the literature,
 and because a periodic function on the upper half-plane takes the appearance
 of a self-similar function on the disk.
\layout Standard

The mapping if the upper half-plane to the Poincare disk is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w=\frac{i-\tau}{i+\tau}\label{eq:poincare disk map}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This map is a conformal map that takes points in the upper half-plane to
 points in the interior of a unit disk.
 Points on the real number line (points with a zero imaginary component)
 are mapped to the edge of the disk.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=x+i\epsilon$
\end_inset 

 and take 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset 

; one then has
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w=\frac{i-x}{i+x}=\frac{x^{2}-1+2ix}{x^{2}+1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It is not hard to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $|w|=1$
\end_inset 

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

 is on the edge of the disk.
 A function which is periodic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 with integer periodicity will manifest itself with an M-set like periodicity
 on the circumference of the Poincare disk.
 Specifically, a feature located at integer values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=n$
\end_inset 

 will have a specific angular location on the Poincare disk, which is obtained
 by solving for the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 in
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{n}=\cos\theta_{n}+i\sin\theta_{n}=\frac{n^{2}-1}{n^{2}+1}+i\,\frac{2n}{n^{2}+1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In particular, the region 
\begin_inset Formula $n\le\Re\tau\le n+1$
\end_inset 

 is mapped to the angular interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\theta_{n},\theta_{n+1}]$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Images constructed by mapping the 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

-disk to upper half-plane, via equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:q-disk mapping}

\end_inset 

, will be inherently periodic.
 The Mobius transform 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau\to\tau+m\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 under the 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

-disk mapping takes all such values to exactly the same value of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

.
 An image on the Poincare disk constructed from the image on the 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

-disk will have regions that are identical, by construction.
 
\layout Standard

