\layout Subsection

Numeric Techniques
\layout Standard

This section reviews the numeric techniques applied to perform the series
 sums.
 Specifically, some well-known techniques for series acceleration are applied;
 but these are not so well known as not to merit review.
\layout Standard

Note that the series explored on these pages can be slow to converge, especially
 near the 'horns' of the Mandelbrot set.
 There are several well-known and established techniques of series acceleration
 that can improve the convergence.
 This section quickly reviews the technique used in this paper.
\layout Standard

Consider the sum
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A(t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\exp(-t^{2}n^{2})\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Assume that this sum converges in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset 

, but possibly slowly.
 One can get a much more quickly-converging series by computing, in addition
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset 

, the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $dA(t)/dt$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}A(t)/dt^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 One then recombines these derivatives to form the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B(t)=A(t)-t\,\frac{d}{dt}A(t)-\frac{t^{2}}{2}\,\frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}A(t)\label{eq:quadratic-acccel}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It is clear that if the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $A(0)$
\end_inset 

 exists and is finite, then one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0+}B(t)=\lim_{t\rightarrow0+}A(t)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and furthermore, for small 
\begin_inset Formula $t,$
\end_inset 

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B(t)=A(0)+\mathcal{O}(t^{3})\label{eq:series-accel}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The correctness of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:series-accel}

\end_inset 

 at first seems naively 'obvious' but is in fact quite subtle, and depends
 on having a series 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ a_{n}\}$
\end_inset 

 that is 'well-behaved' in certain ways.
\layout Standard

The study of such series and the numerical techniques to sum them falls
 under the name of 'series acceleration' and is a well-developed branch
 of mathematics in its own right.
 It is outside of the scope of this section to review any deeper results.
 Suffice it to say that this entire paper is predicated on the assumption
 that the equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:series-accel}

\end_inset 

 does hold for the sums encountered.
 This does seem to be the case, but is hardly obvious from first principles,
 especially for points in troublesome sections of the M-set.
 By contrast, in the well-behaved areas of the M-set, it is straightforward
 to verify that equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:series-accel}

\end_inset 

 holds, and that the resulting sums are accurate for five to ten decimal
 places, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 values in the range of 0.01 to 0.001 for sums with 2 to 50 thousand terms.
 
\layout Standard

Some of the sums in encountered in this paper are divergent.
 The simplest such sums have a limit point, namely 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}a_{n}=\textrm{const.}\neq0\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 in which case one has
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A(t)=\frac{\textrm{const.}}{t}\,\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{4}}+\mathcal{O}(1)\label{eq: dive-sum}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The extra factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\pi}/2$
\end_inset 

 comes from the behavior of the Gaussian regulator; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
N(t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\exp(-t^{2}n^{2})=\frac{1}{t}\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{4}}+\mathcal{O}(1)\label{eq:gaussian-norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In order to correctly subtract this linear divergence from a divergent
 sum, one is advised to subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t)$
\end_inset 

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $1/t$
\end_inset 

 directly.
 This advice comes from the need to subtract the divergence so that the
 equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:series-accel}

\end_inset 

 is not violated.
 In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t)$
\end_inset 

 will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(1)$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(t^{2})$
\end_inset 

 terms as well, any one of which will mess up equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:series-accel}

\end_inset 

 if not properly accounted for.
 Thus, in general, the correct way to subtract a divergent term is to form
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A'(t)=A(t)-\textrm{const. }N(t)\label{eq: subtract-dive}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and then form 
\begin_inset Formula $B'(t)$
\end_inset 

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $A'(t)$
\end_inset 

 to obtain the finite part.
 One can perform the subtraction 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: subtract-dive}

\end_inset 

 under the summation, or outside of it.
 Performing it under the summation potentially minimizes round-off errors.
 Note that these considerations apply to series with limit cycles as well
 as limit points.
 That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 need not converge to a point; as long as they do converge to a limit cycle,
 this mechanism of subtracting the divergent piece will work.
 
\layout Standard

One final remark: note that, in general, after removing a linear divergence
 in a summation, the next leading order need not be finite, but may be a
 weaker divergence, such as a logarithmic divergence.
 This is presumably the nature of the divergences seen at the horns of the
 M-set, for example.
 On the complex plane, finite sums grow until they hit a pole.
 At the pole, the sums are logarithmically divergent.
